

## 🧠 Idea (in simple terms)

* If the element exists → return its index
* If it doesn’t → return the index where it **should be inserted** to keep the array sorted

👉 The trick:
At the end of binary search, the pointer `si` naturally lands at the correct insert position.

---

## ⚙️ Approach

* Use standard binary search
* Keep narrowing the range:

  * If `nums[mid] < target` → go right
  * If `nums[mid] > target` → go left
* If found → return index
* If not found → return `si`

---

## 💻 Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int searchInsert(int[] nums, int target) {
        int si = 0;
        int ei = nums.length - 1;

        while (si <= ei) {
            int mid = si + (ei - si) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] == target) {
                return mid;
            } else if (nums[mid] < target) {
                si = mid + 1;
            } else if (nums[mid] > target) {
                ei = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return si;
    }
}


## ⏱️ Complexity

* Time: `O(log n)`
* Space: `O(1)`

---

## 📌 Key Observations

* `si` always points to the **smallest index where target can fit**
* No extra handling needed after loop — just return `si`
* Works for all edge cases:

  * insert at beginning
  * insert at end
  * insert in between

